### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

compiler

### Description

In a large Angular app it can happen that circular dependency injection is introduced - and this leads to run-time errors. It would be very handy to get an error already during static code analysis at compile time.

The simplest case that should be detected is this:

```ts
// a.service.ts
@Injectable()
export class A {
  private readonly b = inject(B);
}

// b.service.ts
@Injectable()
export class B {
  private readonly a = inject(A);
}
```

But of course, it's not as easy to track down if you have more services in between.


### Proposed solution

If there is a circular dependency injection, there should be a compile-time error

### Alternatives considered

- Currently, you get a run-time error. So if you're lucky and have good test coverage, tests will also detect this issue.
- Th eslint rule `import/no-cycle` implies that there are no dependency injection circles - but there are cases e.g. when you use `forwardRef()` where you might have import cycles - but still don't want circular dependency injection.
- This request is similar to #48976 but (slightly) different: The error should not just detect problems for standalone components, but everywhere when dependency injection is used.
- I suggested this as eslint rule first (https://github.com/angular-eslint/angular-eslint/issues/2082) and @JamesHenry said that this should rather be a framework feature.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

language-service

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

The Angular language service doesn't highlight `readonly` signal inputs as inputs. It also doesn't do this for decorator `@Inputs` but making those `readonly` doesn't make a lot of sense anyway.

Example code:
```ts
import { Component, Input, input } from '@angular/core';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-signal-test',
  standalone: true,
  template: '',
})
export class SignalTestComponent {
  public readonly readonlySignalInput = input<number>();
  public regularSignalInput = input<number>();

  @Input()
  public readonly readonlyDecoratorInput: number | undefined;
  @Input()
  public regularDecoratorInput: number | undefined;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [SignalTestComponent],
  template: `<app-signal-test
    [readonlySignalInput]="123"
    [regularSignalInput]="123"
    [readonlyDecoratorInput]="123"
    [regularDecoratorInput]="123"
  />`,
})
export class PlaygroundComponent {}

bootstrapApplication(PlaygroundComponent);
```

Result when holding ctrl and hovering the readonly signal input in vscode:
![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/126a6eed-b6b7-443f-a61a-d098c6493f96)


Compared to the regular signal input:
![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c21f53d9-86aa-49df-a491-1fad3bfce20e)


`readonly` signal inputs also do not find any usage of them when clicking "Find All References".

